+\subsection{The original capacitance and transition hypothesis}
+\label{subsec:original_capacitance_transition_hypothesis}
+
+\textbf{[ORIGIN / HISTORICAL BRIDGE].}
+The early construction combined the classical relations
+\begin{align}
+    E_{\mathrm{cap}}
+    &=
+    \frac{Q^2}{2C_{\mathrm{cap}}},
+    &
+    C_{\mathrm{cap}}
+    &=
+    \varepsilon\frac{A}{D},
+    \label{eq:origin_capacitance_pair}
+    \\
+    v_{\mathrm{ex}}
+    &=
+    f\lambda,
+    &
+    E
+    &=
+    hf.
+    \label{eq:origin_speed_planck_pair}
+\end{align}
+
+With the historical geometric ansatz $A=\lambda^2$ and $D=\lambda/2$, the
+capacity becomes proportional to $\varepsilon\lambda$. Substitution of
+$\lambda=v_{\mathrm{ex}}/f$ then produces a coefficient multiplying $f$ in the
+stored-energy expression. Under that specific normalization, the historical
+construction may be summarized as
+\begin{align}
+    h_{\mathrm{bridge}}
+    =
+    \frac{Q^2}{4\varepsilon v_{\mathrm{ex}}}.
+    \label{eq:historical_h_capacitance_bridge}
+\end{align}
+
+Equation~\eqref{eq:historical_h_capacitance_bridge} is not a current derivation
+of Planck's constant. It depends on an assumed interaction geometry, on the
+identification of the relevant charge, on a pre-existing electromagnetic
+susceptibility, and on a speed that was itself calibrated from known particle
+relations. Moreover, its later impedance form is an exact reparameterization of
+this same algebraic construction, not an independent second route. Its canonical
+value is that it exposes the original physical question:
+\begin{quote}
+Can the linear energy--frequency law arise from the static and dynamic response
+of a finite transition region rather than being inserted as an unexplained
+proportionality?
+\end{quote}
