+\subsection{Preregistered falsifiers}
+\label{subsec:genesis_preregistered_falsifiers}
+
+The impedance and non-circularity program fails in its strong form if any of the
+following persists after controlled numerical and analytical refinement:
+
+\begin{enumerate}
+    \item no stable transverse link branch exists;
+    \item the inferred propagation speed depends irreducibly on polarization,
+    lattice orientation, or vortex species at low energy;
+    \item the value of $c_T$ can match experiment only by inserting a parameter
+    whose provenance already contains $c$;
+    \item the transition action or source unit remains continuously tunable
+    rather than dynamically or topologically quantized;
+    \item the impedance-ratio route reproduces $\alpha$ only after
+    $\alpha$-dependent calibration;
+    \item the free torsion pulse necessarily creates permanent material
+    vorticity in an initially irrotational region, contrary to the declared
+    Helmholtz sector separation;
+    \item clock slowing, rod response, synchronization, and propagation require
+    mutually inconsistent characteristic speeds;
+    \item alternative microparameters fit $c$ and $\alpha$ equally well while
+    making incompatible predictions elsewhere, without a dynamical selection
+    principle;
+    \item the selected knot geometry changes topology, component linking data,
+    or strict near-ideal classification under the declared refinement pipeline;
+    \item scalar ropelength converges while the positive strut/kink contact
+    measures or active rigidity rank fail to converge;
+    \item a downstream mass, impedance, or constant extraction quotes precision
+    parametrically smaller than the certified geometry-error envelope without an
+    independent cancellation proof.
+\end{enumerate}
+
